answers.body_markdown:
Anything with a `boolean` assignment should do. In C++, true is any non-zero value. In Java, `boolean` is a type (and that type is checked). For example,

    bool a = 1;

is legal C++. But

    boolean a = 1;

is not legal Java. Also, as noted by [@akuzmiykh](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/60943159/for-what-types-of-a-and-b-is-the-simple-assignment-statement-a-b-legal-in-c/60943187#comment107820377_60943187) the reverse is also true, that is

    int a = true;

is legal C++, but not legal Java.

Consider the following.

```
class Foo {
   private int a;
   private int b;
   Foo() {}  // only constructor and is created by compiler
   public void setA(int aval) {
      a = aval;
   }
   public void setB(int bval) {
      b = bval;
   }
}
```
Here is how the values would be set for above.
```
Foo foo = new Foo(); // uses default constructor
foo.setA(10);
foo.setB(20);
```
Now add these constructors to the above
```
Foo() {} // must be added manually now since you
         // are adding your own constructor.  If you don&#39;t you
         // must use the argument version to create an instance
Foo(int a, int b) {
   a = aval;
   b = bval;
}
```
And create an instance like this.
```
Foo f = new Foo(10,20);  // tada! values are set.
```
You can still initialize the values as in the first example if you included the default constructor.  The setters allow you to also change them at any time. 

Not included in the example but you must use `getters` to retrieve the values as they are declared `private`.  Declaring fields private hides implementation details and also allows one to enforce constraints on the fields.

